<DOC><DOCNO> AP890715-0118 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-89 1757EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-15 0390</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0399</SECOND><HEAD>Storms Soak Kansas, Missouri</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Thunderstorms spattered heavy rain on parts of northeast Kansasand northwest Missouri on Saturday, flooding streets in the KansasCity area.   Heavy rain fell from Topeka to Kansas City, 60 miles to the east.More than 2 inches of rain fell in one hour at Kansas CityInternational Airport.   Flooding from heavy rains also occurred Saturday morning in thenortheast Texas counties of Delta, Hopkins and Hunt.   Rain and scattered thunderstorms extended from southeastMinnesota and southwest Wisconsin along the Mississippi Valley tothe Gulf Coast. Showers and thunderstorms also rumbled across theGulf Coast and South Atlantic coastal states. Columbia, S.C., hadmore than 1{ inches of rain in one hour Saturday.   In the West, an area of low pressure extended from the desertSouthwest across Nevada to Idaho. Unstable air producedthunderstorms across portions of eastern Washington, Idaho andextreme western Montana.   Thunderstorms developed Saturday afternoon over southwest Texasand across the New Mexico and Colorado Rockies.   A high pressure system across the Northeast, however, kept theregion dry Saturday.   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDTincluded more than 1{ inches at Topeka, El Dorado, Ariz., andColumbia.   Temperatures at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 59 degrees at Oak Harbor,Wash., to 104 degrees at Gila Bend, Ariz., and Phoenix. The low inthe Lower 48 on Saturday was 30 degrees at Truckee, Calif.   The forecast for Sunday called for scattered thunderstorms fromthe middle and south Atlantic Coast states across the TennesseeValley and the Gulf coastal states to portions of the southernPlains; and scattered showers and thunderstorms from the lower OhioValley across the middle and upper Mississippi Valley to UpperMichigan. Scattered thunderstorms were to develop over westernportions of the Plains, the Rocky Mountains and the northern plateauregion. Rain was expected to develop on the Washington coast.   Predicted high temperatures were in the 60s and 70s along thePacific Coast and across Washington state; 70s from portions of theupper and middle Mississippi Valley across the Great Lakes regionand the northern half of the Appalachians to New England; 100s inportions of south-central and southwest Texas and some sections ofUtah; 100 to 115 degrees in the desert Southwest; and 80s and 90selsewhere.</TEXT></DOC>